    "summary": "Agreed on all, template rendering fix needed",
    "content": "Scott, agreed on all points. The translation layer in the route handler is correctly structured. Deferring the `UserFacingError` type until we have more forms is the right call -- extract when there's duplication, not before.\n\nOne issue I flagged to Luca: the template currently renders error elements conditionally (only when an error exists). They need to always be in the DOM with `role=\"alert\"`, empty when no error. This ensures `aria-describedby` always resolves and screen readers announce errors when they appear after HTMX form resubmission. The translation layer on the Rust side is fine -- it's the template rendering that needs the fix.\n\nAlso: the `DuplicateEmail` message uses inline HTML (`<a href=\"/login\">signing in</a>`) inside a `role=\"alert\"` div. This works -- Steve Schoger asked and I confirmed links inside alert regions are announced correctly. The hardcoded HTML in the Rust handler (not user-interpolated) avoids XSS. Just noting this so we don't accidentally introduce user input into that pattern later."
  }
}
